{
  "texts": [
    "So, despite the collaborative nature of much scientific research, the individual author continues to be a primary unit of recognition.",
    "Mainly because of the 'publish or perish' culture, individual scientists' careers are closely tied to their publication records.",
    "This culture is enhanced by the expansion of scientific journals, academic publishing, and the development of citation indexes, providing metrics for evaluating individual contributions (Garfield 2006).",
    "If we consider this brief historical examination of authorship, we can see that this concept is not ontologically stable but depends on the relationship between certain social conditions (such as the social systems engaged-religion or the rise of science), the technology present at the time (such as the printing press), and individual engagement and authenticity.",
    "The historicity of authorship, in fact, is the history of the process of autopoiesis within the complex eco-systemic environment of the written word."
  ]
}